alliative radiotherapy is being used commonly to relieve local pain from uncomplicated bone metastases at single or multiple sites, in metastatic spinal cord compression, and impending pathological fractures. 70-80% of patients who receive local radiotherapy to relieve bone pain respond to it and up to one-third achieve a complete response.  single dose of 8 y is adequate and optimal for palliation for the patient with localized metastatic bone pain. here is generally no role for multifraction treatment in uncomplicated bone metastasis.[54]  large proportion of patients receiving single-dose radiotherapy for metastatic bone pain are likely to require retreatment. verall, around 25% of patients are retreated after a single dose of radiation. etreatment is both feasible and effective after single doses of 8 y, even over the spinal cord, and a further single dose of 8 y or a fractionated schedule of 20 y in five fractions is perfectly safe.[55] etreatment should be considered in all patients who have persistent or recurrent bone pain. enerally, response reaches a plateau at 4-6 weeks after treatment, and so patients should be encouraged to wait at least 4 weeks after treatment before considering retreatment. ften patients have pain at multiple sites, flitting from one site to another. n such patients, local radiotherapy is unsatisfactory and may require multiple treatment visits. ide-field or hemi-body radiotherapy should be considered in such patients. n patients with metastatic spinal cord compression, surgical decompression is the treatment. owever, patients with a poor performance status, poor survival prognosis, and involvement of multiple spinal segments are candidates for radiotherapy. etastatic lesions with a high risk of fracturing require elective surgical stabilisation. ainful low-risk lesions, however, can be treated conservatively using external beam radiotherapy. adiotherapy is also given after surgical stabilization to induce remineralization of the fractured bone and to stabilize the osteosynthetic prosthesis.ROLE OF PALLIATIVE RADIOTHERAPY TO BONE IN METASTATIC PROSTATE CANCER
Palliative radiotherapy is being used commonly to relieve local pain from uncomplicated bone metastases at single or multiple sites, in metastatic spinal cord compression, and impending pathological fractures. 70-80% of patients who receive local radiotherapy to relieve bone pain respond to it and up to one-third achieve a complete response. A single dose of 8 Gy is adequate and optimal for palliation for the patient with localized metastatic bone pain. There is generally no role for multifraction treatment in uncomplicated bone metastasis.[54] A large proportion of patients receiving single-dose radiotherapy for metastatic bone pain are likely to require retreatment. Overall, around 25% of patients are retreated after a single dose of radiation. Retreatment is both feasible and effective after single doses of 8 Gy, even over the spinal cord, and a further single dose of 8 Gy or a fractionated schedule of 20 Gy in five fractions is perfectly safe.[55] Retreatment should be considered in all patients who have persistent or recurrent bone pain. Generally, response reaches a plateau at 4-6 weeks after treatment, and so patients should be encouraged to wait at least 4 weeks after treatment before considering retreatment. Often patients have pain at multiple sites, flitting from one site to another. In such patients, local radiotherapy is unsatisfactory and may require multiple treatment visits. Wide-field or hemi-body radiotherapy should be considered in such patients. In patients with metastatic spinal cord compression, surgical decompression is the treatment. However, patients with a poor performance status, poor survival prognosis, and involvement of multiple spinal segments are candidates for radiotherapy. Metastatic lesions with a high risk of fracturing require elective surgical stabilisation. Painful low-risk lesions, however, can be treated conservatively using external beam radiotherapy. Radiotherapy is also given after surgical stabilization to induce remineralization of the fractured bone and to stabilize the osteosynthetic prosthesis.
